h the **Starlink** offering and is disaggregated into the following categories:\n    *   **Consumer:** Broadband internet subscriptions and services for individual consumers, including those in remote areas.\n    *   **Enterprise & Government:** Connectivity solutions tailored for businesses and government entities. This category also includes **Starlink Mobile** (satellite-to-mobile texting and voice services for mobile users).\n    *   **Products:** All hardware/product revenue (such as Starlink user terminals/dishes) is attributed entirely to the Connectivity segment.\n\n### 3. AI Segment\nThis segment operates a vertically integrated AI platform that spans frontier Large Language Models (LLM), consumer/enterprise AI solutions, computational infrastructure, and the social media platform X.\n*   **How it generates revenue:** Revenue is disaggregated into two primary categories:\n    *   **Advertising:** Revenue generated from the X platform (described as a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform).\n    *   **AI Solutions & Infrastructure:** Revenue generated from AI products like **Grok Business** and **Grok Enterprise**, which cater to specific workflows and security needs. These are sold using **license-based, consumption-based, or outcome-based pricing models**. It also includes revenue from AI computational infrastructure. \n\n***\n\n**Summary of Segment Synergy:**\nSpaceX\'s business model relies on extreme vertical integration. The **Space** segment acts as the foundational backbone, providing the launch capacity required to deploy the **Connectivity** segment\'s Starlink constellation and, increasingly, the orbital data centers/infrastructure required for the **AI** segment. While Space drives the physical infrastructure, the Connectivity and AI segments are highlighted as the primary drivers of near-term revenue growth and scale.',
